Introduction ¶

Loan prediction is a very basic real-life issue that any retail bank will face at some point during its existence. It can save a lot of man hours at the end of a retail bank if done correctly.Banks' primary business is lending. The primary source of benefit is the interest on the loan. After an extensive verification and confirmation process, the loan companies issue a loan. They may not, however, have guarantees that the borrower will be able to repay the loan without difficulty.

There is a company called Dream House finance company which deals in all type of Loans and have made their presence across all rural, semi-urban and urban areas. They want to build up this process where they automate the eligibilty process based on the details provided by the applicants via online application form.

The aim of Phase I of this study is to look into the impact of various factors on predicting the applicant's probablity status. Many variables, such as Gender, Marital Status, Number of Dependents, Income, Loan Amount, Credit History, and others, have been discovered to play a significant role in predicting eligibility status.

Dataset Source¶

The data is Sourced from (https://www.kaggle.com/altruistdelhite04/loan-prediction-problem-dataset?select=train_u6lujuX_CVtuZ9i.csv). The data set includes 614 observations and 13 feature information

Dataset Details¶

The data is about loan status getting approved or not for an individual taking various factors into consideration such as how much is the loan amount they have applied for or whether its a Male or Female or depending on it Credit History or how many dependents he/she has etc. These all factors will help us in predicting whether an individual will be able to repay the amount or not depending on which a loan of particular amount will be granted to him/her.

Dataset Features¶

The variable descriptions below are:

Feature Data type Unit Description
Gender Binary Unknown Male/ Female
Maritial status Binary Unknown Married(Yes/No)
Dependents Ordinal Unknown No. of dependents of the Applicants
Education Binary Unknown Applicant Graduate (Graduate/Not)
Self_Employed Binary Unknown Self-Employed(Yes/No)
Loan_Amount_Term Numerical Thousands Term of loan in months)
Credit_History Numerical Unknown credit history meets guidelines
Property_Area Numerical Unknown Urban/ Semi Urban/ Rural
Loan_Status Binary Unknown Loan approved (Yes/No)

Target Feature¶

The target feature for our project is "Loan_Status" which has two levels.

  1. No="If Loan is not approved "
  2. Yes="If Loan is approved"

We will be predicting "The probablity of Loan approval" based on the information received of the applicants.

Goals & Objective

The goal of this study is to look into the impact of various factors on predicting the applicant's Loan approval status.  Variables  such as Gender, Marital Status, Number of Dependents, Loan Amount, Credit History, and others, have been discovered to play a significant role in predicting eligibility status.

Since there are so many missing values, we can't just leave them out. Categorical Variables account for the majority of missing values. As a result, we can consider the following approaches to fill in the missing values:

  • For numerical variables, use mean or median imputation.
  • For categorical variables, use mode imputation.

Summary & Conclusion

Out of a total of 614 applicants, 422 had their loan status accepted, according to the data review. The majority of male applicants with no dependents received a loan, while the majority of female applicants with dependents did not. According to analysis, 47 percent of married applicants were eligible for a loan, compared to 22 percent of unmarried applicants. Those that have 0 dependents have a better chance of having their loan accepted. Graduates have a higher chance of being accepted for a loan than those who do not have a degree. Graduate applicants have a 10% higher loan acceptance rate than under graduate applicants.

Applicants with no credit history are less likely to be accepted, owing to a higher risk of defaulting. Applicants with a credit history have a 68 percent chance of getting their loan accepted. This implies that credit history and loan approval are linked in some way.

There is not really any relationship between Loan Status and Self-Employed applicants. Along these lines, to put it plainly, we can say that the applicants who have some fixed income are probably going to be considered for loan approval. Applicants with credit history not passing guidelines mostly fails to get approved, probably because they have a higher chances of not paying back. 68% of the applicants who have credit history are probably going to have their loan approved. This recommend that credit history and Loan approval have some relation. Around 29% of applicants living in semi-metropolitan property territory will in general have their loan approved. Assuming you have solid Co-Applicant, then it most likely to have their loan approved.

The Income of an Applicant plays an important role in getting a loan approved as we know most of the loans are requested by the applicants with low income. The applicant Gender plays an important role too. Most of the male applicants who are married have higher incomes than female married applicants which helps them in getting their loan approved much more easily.
